@* THE CONTROL FOR decision 168, AND IT IS THE SAME FILE WITH THE @ref MOVED ONE ELEMENT.

   Unsupported/Gate/RefInRow.razor captures the row's own <li>; this file captures an <li> that sits
   OUTSIDE the @foreach, in the same <ul>, with the same field name and the same handler. It compiles
   clean and emits `const row = document.createElement('li');` at MOUNT scope, where
   `listen(_el4, 'click', async () => { await row.focus(); })` can see it -- so the refusal next door
   is located on the region and on NOTHING else: not on @ref, not on the list, not on @key, not on the
   async handler.

   It is also the WORKAROUND the diagnostic names: move the @ref onto an element outside the
   @foreach/@if.

   VALID BLAZOR: dotnet build of this source in a real Blazor WebAssembly project succeeds. *@
<ul id="list"><li id="head" @ref="row">head</li><button id="add" @onclick="Add">add</button>@foreach (Row r in _rows)
{
    <li @key="r.Id"><span class="lbl">@r.Label</span></li>
}</ul><button id="go" @onclick="Focus">go</button>

@code {
    record Row
    {
        public int Id { get; set; }
        public string Label { get; set; } = "";
    }

    private List<Row> _rows = new List<Row>();
    private int _next = 1;
    private ElementReference row;

    private void Add()
    {
        Row r = new Row();
        r.Id = _next;
        r.Label = "task " + _next;
        _next = _next + 1;
        _rows.Add(r);
    }

    async Task Focus() { await row.FocusAsync(); }
}
